# Telegram Inline Buttons

Send a message with Yes/No (or any) inline button choices to a Telegram chat.
The user's tap is delivered back to you as a plain text message.

## How to use

Write a JSON file to the IPC messages directory:

```bash
cat > /workspace/ipc/messages/buttons-$(date +%s%N).json << 'EOF'
{
  "type": "message_with_buttons",
  "chatJid": "CHAT_JID",
  "text": "Your question here",
  "buttons": [["Yes", "No"]]
}
EOF
```

Replace `CHAT_JID` with the JID of the chat (e.g. `tg:8514304397`).
The `CHAT_JID` for the current conversation is available in your system prompt.

## Button layout

`buttons` is an array of rows. Each row is an array of button labels.

```json
"buttons": [["Yes", "No"]]           // one row, two buttons
"buttons": [["Option A"], ["Option B"], ["Option C"]]  // three rows
"buttons": [["Confirm", "Cancel"]]   // one row
```

## Example: confirm before creating a calendar event

```bash
cat > /workspace/ipc/messages/confirm-$(date +%s%N).json << 'EOF'
{
  "type": "message_with_buttons",
  "chatJid": "tg:8514304397",
  "text": "Create a calendar event for this?",
  "buttons": [["Yes", "No"]]
}
EOF
```

After writing the file, stop and wait. The user's button tap will arrive as your
next message (e.g. `"Yes"` or `"No"`). Then act on it.

## Notes

- Only works on Telegram chats (jid starting with `tg:`)
- Falls back to plain text on channels that don't support buttons
- The button label is the callback data — keep labels short and unambiguous
